III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

ΔΙΟΡΘΩΜΈΝΟ ΚΕΊΜΕΝΟ:
Ajax, whose mother was Eriboea (569). —τὸν εἰσαεὶ .. χρόνον : the phrase τὸν ἀεὶ χρόνον is frequent. The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Cp. Thuc. I. II § 1 (the Greeks at Troy) φαίνονται...πρὸς γεωργίαν τῆς Χερσονήσου τραπόμενοι καὶ λῃστείαν τῆς τροφῆς ἀπορίᾳ. The Iliad glances at such predatory expeditions (e.g. I. 366; 9. 328).—Note the light touch with which the poet accounts for the absence of Teucer—a necessity of the plot, since Teucer might have averted his brotherʼs suicide. 344 . ἀνοίγετε: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house generally; Aesch. Ch. 877 ἀλλʼ ἀνοίξατε: Ter. Adelph. 4. 4. 26 aperite, aliquis. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο προέρχεται από ένα κλασικό σχόλιο- είναι γραμμένο κυρίως σε μια σύγχρονη γλώσσα (αγγλικά, γαλλικά, γερμανικά ή ιταλικά) και μπορεί να περιέχει αλληλουχίες λέξεων σε αρχαίες γλώσσες (αρχαία ελληνικά και λατινικά). Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο εμφανίζεται μετά το τμήμα "ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ ΠΡΟΣ ΔΙΟΡΘΩΣΗ:". Παρακαλείστε να τοποθετήσετε τη διορθωμένη έκδοση του κειμένου μετά το τμήμα "ΔΙΟΡΘΩΜΕΝΟ ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ:". Μην γράψετε τίποτε άλλο εκτός από το διορθωμένο κείμενο.

prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

Βοηθήστε στην εξέταση και διόρθωση σφαλμάτων σε κείμενα που παράγονται από την αυτόματη μεταγραφή (OCR) ιστορικών εγγράφων. Ο στόχος σας είναι να εξετάσετε προσεκτικά το ακόλουθο κείμενο και να διορθώσετε τυχόν λάθη που εισήχθησαν από το λογισμικό OCR. Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο προέρχεται από ένα κλασικό σχόλιο- είναι γραμμένο κυρίως σε μια σύγχρονη γλώσσα (αγγλικά, γαλλικά, γερμανικά ή ιταλικά) και μπορεί να περιέχει αλληλουχίες λέξεων σε αρχαίες γλώσσες (αρχαία ελληνικά και λατινικά). Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο εμφανίζεται μετά το τμήμα "ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ ΠΡΟΣ ΔΙΟΡΘΩΣΗ:". Παρακαλείστε να τοποθετήσετε τη διορθωμένη έκδοση του κειμένου μετά το τμήμα "ΔΙΟΡΘΩΜΕΝΟ ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ:". Μην γράψετε τίποτε άλλο εκτός από το διορθωμένο κείμενο.

dvolyere: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house enerally; Aesch.

prediction.line: lsaeus Cir. p. 69. §. 11. μὴ θέλοι Lycurg. Leocr. p. 157, 77.
prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

III. p. 154. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Λείας. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Hesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur τοῖς κυσί, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur ; idemque sensisse videtur qui v. 232. adscripsit : οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjecturam sequun- tur. Rectius Schol. Rom. τοῖς ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, ἵνα μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων τὸ σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. Δ. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra scripto νέμει. Illud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p. 306. e glossa εἰς αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. Xl. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. prediction.line: tur. Rectius Schol. Rom. τοῖς ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο,
prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

ocr.line: s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. l.
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

ocr.line: λήν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph.
ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. V. 14, 116, Plutarch Lucull. c. XXXIV, cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49, "πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον" in Dio Chrysostom. VII. 226, "πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα" in Euripides Hel. 598, "γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος" in Sophocles Oed. C. 1686, "τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν" in Aeschylus Eum. 76.

ocr.region: adjici ut lectores integrioris formae admoneantur. Mr θελήσας Isaeus Cir. p.69. $.11. zu} θέλοι Lycurg. Leoer. p. 157, 77. etc. et similia apud Demosthenem, cui Schaeferus μὴ ἐθέλειν eximere studet ad p. 1451, 61. cf. Ruediger ad Philipp. I. p. 27. Thuoydidi familiarius verbum trisyllabum , nee dubita- tione caruit ei θέλοιμεν VI. 34, A. sed Platoni jure reli- quit Schneiderus ad Civ. T. I. p. 230. T. III. p. 15%. etsi apud hunc ut apud ceteros antiquiores praevalet ἐθέλειν. V. 25. Ἐφθαρμένας — Hunc et insequentem versum producit Suidas s. Asius. Verbum κατηναρισμένας ex h. l. idem et Ilesychius et Schol. Ven. XXI. 26. enotarunt. Quod sequitur, ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις, id Suidas s. Ἐπιστάτις in- terpretatur zeig «vol, fortasse ne Ajax caedis verae nec ad vindictam necessariae reus agatur; idemque sensisse videtur gui v. 232. adseripsit: οὗτοι γὰρ ἐνόμιζον καὶ ποιμένας αὐτὸν ἀνῃρηκέναι, id est, solam in hoc conjeciuram sequun- tur. _Rectius Schol. Rom. zoig ποιμέσι· καλῶς δὲ τοῦτο, iva μὴ παραγένοιτό τις ἀπαγγέλλων To σαφές. Sic ποιμ- νίων ἐπιστάταις Plat. Legg. X. 906. A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει. Codd. A. La. Lb. Aug. B. τρέπει, hic supra seripto νέμει. IIlud Valckenarius ad Hipp. p- 306. e,glossa eis αὐτὸν τρέπει ortum putat. Galenus de Plenit. c. XI. 346. T. VII. Chart. p. 582. Kuehn. οὐκ ἴσην ἅπασι νέμει τὴν alviav. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρ- εἰσιδών — haec verba ap- ponit Thomas s. Orryje, lolum versum cum insequenti Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, quam vocem Eustathius p. 788, 31. ex h. |. affert. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα nedie. E Scholiastae interpreta- mento τῷ πεδίῳ nata est codd. nonnullorum lectio πεδίῳ. Syntaxis hujus exempla abunde multa extant, sed regula parum claret; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην lesai. XVI. 8. πολ- λὴν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenoph. Eph. V. 14, 116. Plutarch. Lucull. e. XXXIV. cf. Aglaoph. T. I. 49. πολὺν πλανᾷσθαι τόπον Dio Chr. VII. 226. πᾶσαν πλανηθεὶς χθόνα Eur. Hel. 598. γῆν ἀπίαν ἀλώμενος Oed. C. 1686: τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν Beßus Aesch. Eum. 76.

prediction.region: 25. Ἐφθαρμένας - Suidas also includes this verse after the previous one. The word "κατηναρισμένας" is mentioned by Hesychius and the Scholia Veneta in the same context. What follows, "ποιμνίων ἐπιστάταις," is interpreted by Suidas as meaning "sheep leaders," perhaps suggesting that Ajax should not be accused of true murder or necessary revenge; the same seems to be suggested by the one who wrote line 232: "for they believed that even the shepherds killed him," that is, they only follow this conjecture. It is more correct to follow the Scholia Romana, which suggests "shepherds"; but it is good to add this, so that no one might report something ambiguous. Thus we have "sheep leaders" in Plato's Laws X.906A. V. 28. Αἰτίαν νέμει - Codices A, La, Lb, Aug. B. read "τρέπει" but a previous mention of "νέμει" has been written. Valckenarius, in his commentary on Hippocrates, suggests that it should be read as "τρέπει". Galen in his work On Fullness, Chapter XI, also supports this interpretation. V. 29. Keil μοί τις ὀπτήρεις - Thomas Orrie quotes these words, along with the following line, from Suidas s. Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius also quotes on line 788, 31. Ep. Pr. V. 30. Πηδῶντα. The reading "τῷ πεδίῳ" is derived from the interpretation of the Scholiast, but some manuscripts read "πεδίῳ". There are numerous examples of this construction, but the rule is not clear; "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" in Lesae XVI. 8, "πολλὴν ἐρημίαν" in Conon Narr. II, "πολλὴν γῆν" in Xenophon Eph. the fiery man. Essay on L. §9. P. 12, 2. If τοι is retained in infr. 245, we may read here οἵαν ἐδήλωσας *kar avdpis αἴθονος. The short syllable in αἴθονος is sufficiently supported by at6ova occur- ring in Hesychius in the right alpha- betical order (immediately after alo1). Although αἴθοπος (see v. r1.) may be defended, on the ground that the second part of a compound has sometimes little significance (see esp. infr. 954, κελαι- νῶπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here, and has the preponderance of MS. authority in its favour. 222. ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν] ‘That can neither be avoided nor endared.’ 225. μεγάλων] ‘Terrible.’ The mari- ners, in their feebleness (supr. 165 foll.), are afraid of the opinion of the host. These words are added as a commenut on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ pyasus) ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, & μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in geneial. ἀέξει] Not "exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’

Although αἴθοπος (see v. r1.) may be defended, on the ground that the second part of a compound has sometimes little significance (see esp. infr. 954, κελαι- νῶπαν θυμόν), yet αἴθων, which directly expresses character, is more appropriate here, and has the preponderance of MS. authority in its favour. 222. ἄτλατον οὐδὲ φευκτάν] ‘That can neither be avoided nor endared.’ 225. μεγάλων] ‘Terrible.’ The mari- ners, in their feebleness (supr. 165 foll.), are afraid of the opinion of the host. These words are added as a commenut on οὐδὲ φευκτάν. The consequences of the fact cannot be eluded, since it is known to the host, and magnified by rumour. 226. ὁ pyasus) ‘The formidable power of rumour.’ Supr. 172, & μεγάλα φάτις. μῦθος is the rumour about this particular thing, with a suggestion of rumour in geneial. ἀέξει] Not "exaggerates,’ for the evil could not be exaggerated, but, ‘which the mighty power of rumour spreads abroad.’

And someone, seeing - these words Thomas adds the word Ὀπτήρ, and the whole verse, along with the following verse, Suidas adds the word Ὀπτῆρας, which Eustathius cites from this passage. ED. PR. V. 30. Πηδῶντα πεδία. The reading τῷ πεδίῳ was born from the interpretation of the scholiast, but the reading πεδίῳ is found in the manuscripts of some. There are many examples of this syntax, but the rule is not very clear; πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην Isaiah XVI. 8. πολλήν ἐρημίαν Conon. Narr. II. πολλὴν γῆν Xenophon, Eph. V. 14, 116. C. 1686. τὴν πλανοστιβῆ γῆν βεβώς Aesch, Eum. 76.

ΔΙΟΡΘΩΜΈΝΟ ΚΕΊΜΕΝΟ:
Ajax, whose mother was Eriboea (569). —τὸν εἰσαεὶ .. χρόνον : the phrase τὸν ἀεὶ χρόνον is frequent. The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Cp. Thuc. I. II § 1 (the Greeks at Troy) φαίνονται...πρὸς γεωργίαν τῆς Χερσονήσου τραπόμενοι καὶ λῃστείαν τῆς τροφῆς ἀπορίᾳ. The Iliad glances at such predatory expeditions (e.g. I. 366; 9. 328).—Note the light touch with which the poet accounts for the absence of Teucer—a necessity of the plot, since Teucer might have averted his brotherʼs suicide. 344 . ἀνοίγετε: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house generally; Aesch. Ch. 877 ἀλλʼ ἀνοίξατε: Ter. Adelph. 4. 4. 26 aperite, aliquis. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο προέρχεται από ένα κλασικό σχόλιο- είναι γραμμένο κυρίως σε μια σύγχρονη γλώσσα (αγγλικά, γαλλικά, γερμανικά ή ιταλικά) και μπορεί να περιέχει αλληλουχίες λέξεων σε αρχαίες γλώσσες (αρχαία ελληνικά και λατινικά). Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο εμφανίζεται μετά το τμήμα "ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ ΠΡΟΣ ΔΙΟΡΘΩΣΗ:". Παρακαλείστε να τοποθετήσετε τη διορθωμένη έκδοση του κειμένου μετά το τμήμα "ΔΙΟΡΘΩΜΕΝΟ ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ:". Μην γράψετε τίποτε άλλο εκτός από το διορθωμένο κείμενο.

ΚΕΊΜΕΝΟ ΠΡΟΣ ΔΙΌΡΘΩΣΗ:
dvolyere: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house enerally; Aesch.

ἀνοίγετε: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house generally; Aesch.

Βοηθήστε στην εξέταση και διόρθωση σφαλμάτων σε κείμενα που παράγονται από την αυτόματη μεταγραφή (OCR) ιστορικών εγγράφων. Ο στόχος σας είναι να εξετάσετε προσεκτικά το ακόλουθο κείμενο και να διορθώσετε τυχόν λάθη που εισήχθησαν από το λογισμικό OCR. Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο προέρχεται από ένα κλασικό σχόλιο- είναι γραμμένο κυρίως σε μια σύγχρονη γλώσσα (αγγλικά, γαλλικά, γερμανικά ή ιταλικά) και μπορεί να περιέχει αλληλουχίες λέξεων σε αρχαίες γλώσσες (αρχαία ελληνικά και λατινικά). Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο εμφανίζεται μετά το τμήμα "ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ ΠΡΟΣ ΔΙΟΡΘΩΣΗ:". Παρακαλείστε να τοποθετήσετε τη διορθωμένη έκδοση του κειμένου μετά το τμήμα "ΔΙΟΡΘΩΜΕΝΟ ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ:". Μην γράψετε τίποτε άλλο εκτός από το διορθωμένο κείμενο.

dvolyere: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house enerally; Aesch.

ἀνοίγετε: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house generally; Aesch.

ocr.region: Ajax. We are thus made aware that the crisis of the drama is approaching. But, on the other hand, the bearing of the prophet to Teucer, as reported by the messenger, and the tenor of his prophecy, assure the spectator that the anger of Athena against Ajax is not lasting, and hold forth a vague promise of final peace. GvBpes φίλοι] The messenger, who is one of Teucer’s men, thus assures the mariners of his continued friendship in their master’s hour of need. τὸ πρῶτον stands in apposition with the sentence, Τεῦκρος παρέστι, which, as Hermann says, must be held as equivalent to Ted- xnov παρεῖναι. Cp. O. T. 1234, 5, 6 μὲν τάχιστοός τῶν λόγῶν εἰπεῖν τε Καὶ |μαθεῖν, τέθνηκε θεῖον Ἰοκάστης κάρα. ΔΙΟΡΘΩΜΈΝΟ ΚΕΊΜΕΝΟ:
Ajax, whose mother was Eriboea (569). —τὸν εἰσαεὶ .. χρόνον : the phrase τὸν ἀεὶ χρόνον is frequent. The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Cp. Thuc. I. II § 1 (the Greeks at Troy) φαίνονται...πρὸς γεωργίαν τῆς Χερσονήσου τραπόμενοι καὶ λῃστείαν τῆς τροφῆς ἀπορίᾳ. The Iliad glances at such predatory expeditions (e.g. I. 366; 9. 328).—Note the light touch with which the poet accounts for the absence of Teucer—a necessity of the plot, since Teucer might have averted his brotherʼs suicide. 344 . ἀνοίγετε: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house generally; Aesch. Ch. 877 ἀλλʼ ἀνοίξατε: Ter. Adelph. 4. 4. 26 aperite, aliquis. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

Βοηθήστε στην εξέταση και διόρθωση σφαλμάτων σε κείμενα που παράγονται από την αυτόματη μεταγραφή (OCR) ιστορικών εγγράφων. Ο στόχος σας είναι να εξετάσετε προσεκτικά το ακόλουθο κείμενο και να διορθώσετε τυχόν λάθη που εισήχθησαν από το λογισμικό OCR. Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο προέρχεται από ένα κλασικό σχόλιο- είναι γραμμένο κυρίως σε μια σύγχρονη γλώσσα (αγγλικά, γαλλικά, γερμανικά ή ιταλικά) και μπορεί να περιέχει αλληλουχίες λέξεων σε αρχαίες γλώσσες (αρχαία ελληνικά και λατινικά). Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο εμφανίζεται μετά το τμήμα "ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ ΠΡΟΣ ΔΙΟΡΘΩΣΗ:". Παρακαλείστε να τοποθετήσετε τη διορθωμένη έκδοση του κειμένου μετά το τμήμα "ΔΙΟΡΘΩΜΕΝΟ ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ:". Μην γράψετε τίποτε άλλο εκτός από το διορθωμένο κείμενο.

Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

prediction.region: In his reply, Galenus calmly distinguishes between them. The genitive is at first put vaguely, but a construction is afterwards supplied for it by the addition of "peri." I am in travail to know your meaning. He expressly orders. Confined within the tent. Why? The answer shows that the meaning is rather "For what reason?" than "With what intention?". And he is hoping to convey intelligence that it is fatal for Ajax to go forth as he has now done. This very day, in which he intimates that life or death is in store for him.

Υπάρχουν πολλά παραδείγματα που δείχνουν τη σύνταξη αυτή, αλλά η κανόνας δεν είναι πολύ καθαρός. Παραδείγματα περιλαμβάνουν "πλανηθῆναι τὴν ἐρήμην" (Ιωάννης Δ' Α') και "πολλήν ἐρημίαν" (Κώνων ΙΙ). Το προηγούμενο κακοῖς παρεμβάλλεται στην αναφορική πρόταση, αν και εδώ η πτώση του δεν επηρεάζεται από αυτό: συνοψίζει τι εννοείται με το αόριστο κακοῖς. 274 κανέπνευσε μετά την πραγματική παύση (ἔληξε), απαιτείται ένα μικρό χρονικό διάστημα για την αναπνοή. groundtruth.region: Ajax, whose mother was Eriboea (569). —τὸν εἰσαεὶ .. χρόνον : the phrase τὸν ἀεὶ χρόνον is frequent. The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Cp. Thuc. I. II § 1 (the Greeks at Troy) φαίνονται...πρὸς γεωργίαν τῆς Χερσονήσου τραπόμενοι καὶ λῃστείαν τῆς τροφῆς ἀπορίᾳ. The Iliad glances at such predatory expeditions (e.g. I. 366; 9. 328).—Note the light touch with which the poet accounts for the absence of Teucer—a necessity of the plot, since Teucer might have averted his brotherʼs suicide. 344 . ἀνοίγετε: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house generally; Aesch. Ch. 877 ἀλλʼ ἀνοίξατε: Ter. Adelph. 4. 4. 26 aperite, aliquis. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

Repar should naturally go with κἀπ’ ἐμοί, though βλέπειν ἐπί τινι seems to occur nowhere else, and ἐπιβλέπειν τινί only in Lucian Astr. 20 καὶ σφίσι γνομένοισι τῷ μὲν ἡ Ἀφροδίτη τῷ δὲ ὁ Ζεὺς... ἐπέβλεψαν (‘loocked with favour’). The alternative is to take ἐπ’ uol as= ‘in my case,’ and βλέψας as epexegetic ; but this is certainly harsh. 846 f. διοίγω: cp. O. T. 1287 διοί- γειν kA6pa, and ib. 1295.—mpdyn, deeds: cp. 21. Pe ἐκκύκλημα is now pushed on through the central door. It was a small stage, but large enough to allow of Ajax being shown surrounded by some of the slaugh- tered animals. The word πράγη in 247, and the language of vv. 351 ff., show that the carnage was represented. The other plays in which Sophocles has used the eccyclema are the Antigone (1294, where see n.), and the Electra (1464 f., n.). ocr.sentence: 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere.
ocr.region: πνεύματος ἐπιρροῆῇ ἀέρα ὑγρὸν ἕλκοντες ὥσπερ νήπιοι παῖδες. Pliny H. M. 18. 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 rods ἀνέ- μους purovpyowras. We might add Catull. 62. 39 ut flos.. | Quem mulcent aurae, firmat sol, educat imber.—va ψυχὴν ἀτάλλων. Cp. Tr. 144 τὸ γὰρ νεάζον ἐν τοιοῖσδε βόσκεται| χώροισιν αὐ- τοῦ εἰς. (n.). The word ἀτάλλω (which in Il. 13. 27 means ‘to gambol’) bears the sense of ‘cherishing’ in Hom. epigr. 4. 2 νήπιον αἰδοίης ἐπὶ γούνασι μητρὸς ἀτάλλων, and Pind. fr. 214 γλυκεῖά ol καρδίαν drd\oira... | ἐλπίς. The Homeric form in this sense is ἀτιτάλλω, Od. 18. 323 παῖδα ds ἀτίταλλε. The word drdMw may have been sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromachè: II. 6. 400 παῖδ’ ἐπὶ κόλπῳ ἔχουσ’ ἀταλά- φρονα, νήπιον atrws. χαρμονήν might be acc. in appos. with ψυχὴν only; but is better taken as acc. in agpos. with the whole sentence (see on El 130 ἤκετ’ ἐμῶν καμάτων wapa- utio).—The conjecture χαρμονή is no gain. 880 It is strange that exception should have been taken to the parenthetic οἶδα, which is not rare; cp. 938, O. C. 1615, El. 334. — obros.. p: cp. 83, 421.

ocr.line: the sense of 'cherishingʼ in Hom. epigr.
ocr.region: πνεύματος ἐπιρροῆῇ ἀέρα ὑγρὸν ἕλκοντες ὥσπερ νήπιοι παῖδες. Pliny H. M. 18. 34 Zephyrum dicit in plantas nutricium exercere. Lucian Bis accus. § 1 rods ἀνέ- μους purovpyowras. We might add Catull. 62. 39 ut flos.. | Quem mulcent aurae, firmat sol, educat imber.—va ψυχὴν ἀτάλλων. Cp. Tr. 144 τὸ γὰρ νεάζον ἐν τοιοῖσδε βόσκεται| χώροισιν αὐ- τοῦ εἰς. (n.). The word ἀτάλλω (which in Il. 13. 27 means ‘to gambol’) bears the sense of ‘cherishing’ in Hom. epigr. 4. 2 νήπιον αἰδοίης ἐπὶ γούνασι μητρὸς ἀτάλλων, and Pind. fr. 214 γλυκεῖά ol καρδίαν drd\oira... | ἐλπίς. The Homeric form in this sense is ἀτιτάλλω, Od. 18. 323 παῖδα ds ἀτίταλλε. The word drdMw may have been sug- gested to Sophocles by a trait in the scene between Hector and Andromachè: II. 6. 400 παῖδ’ ἐπὶ κόλπῳ ἔχουσ’ ἀταλά- φρονα, νήπιον atrws. χαρμονήν might be acc. in appos. with ψυχὴν only; but is better taken as acc. in agpos. with the whole sentence (see on El 130 ἤκετ’ ἐμῶν καμάτων wapa- utio).—The conjecture χαρμονή is no gain. 880 It is strange that exception should have been taken to the parenthetic οἶδα, which is not rare; cp. 938, O. C. 1615, El. 334. — obros.. p: cp. 83, 421.

ΔΙΟΡΘΩΜΈΝΟ ΚΕΊΜΕΝΟ:
Ajax, whose mother was Eriboea (569). —τὸν εἰσαεὶ .. χρόνον : the phrase τὸν ἀεὶ χρόνον is frequent. The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Cp. Thuc. I. II § 1 (the Greeks at Troy) φαίνονται...πρὸς γεωργίαν τῆς Χερσονήσου τραπόμενοι καὶ λῃστείαν τῆς τροφῆς ἀπορίᾳ. The Iliad glances at such predatory expeditions (e.g. I. 366; 9. 328).—Note the light touch with which the poet accounts for the absence of Teucer—a necessity of the plot, since Teucer might have averted his brotherʼs suicide. 344 . ἀνοίγετε: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house generally; Aesch. Ch. 877 ἀλλʼ ἀνοίξατε: Ter. Adelph. 4. 4. 26 aperite, aliquis. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο προέρχεται από ένα κλασικό σχόλιο- είναι γραμμένο κυρίως σε μια σύγχρονη γλώσσα (αγγλικά, γαλλικά, γερμανικά ή ιταλικά) και μπορεί να περιέχει αλληλουχίες λέξεων σε αρχαίες γλώσσες (αρχαία ελληνικά και λατινικά). ocr.region: 524. Tekmessa deutet auf 480 zurück, woraus sich ἔτι erklärt, d. h. eis ro ἑξῆς. 525. κἀγώ, El. 527. Aias will gern Tekmessa loben —, nicht aber, wie der Chor räth, ihre Worte, d. h. ihr versprechen, leben zu wollen, son- dern, wie er neoa noosdoxier hinzufügt, wenn sie ihm in allen Stücken folgsam sei. Er sorgt, sie möge ihm den Eurysakes vorent- halten; deutet aber zugleich ver- steckt auf das, was er für seine ungestörte Vorbereitung zum Tode wünscht. 528. Beachte die Allitteration. 1301.

ΚΕΊΜΕΝΟ ΠΡΟΣ ΔΙΌΡΘΩΣΗ:
524. Tekmessa deutet auf 480 zurück, woraus sich ἔτι erklärt, d. h. eis ro ἑξῆς. 525. κἀγώ, El. 527. Aias will gern Tekmessa loben —, nicht aber, wie der Chor räth, ihre Worte, d. h. ihr versprechen, leben zu wollen, son- dern, wie er neoa noosdoxier hinzufügt, wenn sie ihm in allen Stücken folgsam sei. Er sorgt, sie möge ihm den Eurysakes vorent- halten; deutet aber zugleich ver- steckt auf das, was er für seine ungestörte Vorbereitung zum Tode wünscht. 528. Beachte die Allitteration. 1301.

Πέρσαι 378) ημέρας. Βλέπε Ηλ. 19. 674-675. Ο άνεμος που φυσά με δύναμη ηρεμεί και πάλι τη θαλασσοσβεννύεται, επιτρέποντας σε ήπιους ανέμους (βλέπε Οδ. 5, 383. Οβιδ. Αιν. 5, 763.) ή σε παύσης ανέμων. Όρας 1, 3, 15 Ο Νότος δεν είναι ισχυρότερος από τον Άδρια, ανεβαίνει ή κατεβαίνει σύννεφα (με την ιδιότητά του να σηκώνει ή να ρίχνει το ιστίο).

Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο προέρχεται από ένα κλασικό σχόλιο- είναι γραμμένο κυρίως σε μια σύγχρονη γλώσσα (αγγλικά, γαλλικά, γερμανικά ή ιταλικά) και μπορεί να περιέχει αλληλουχίες λέξεων σε αρχαίες γλώσσες (αρχαία ελληνικά και λατινικά). Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο εμφανίζεται μετά το τμήμα "ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ ΠΡΟΣ ΔΙΟΡΘΩΣΗ:". Παρακαλείστε να τοποθετήσετε τη διορθωμένη έκδοση του κειμένου μετά το τμήμα "ΔΙΟΡΘΩΜΕΝΟ ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ:". Μην γράψετε τίποτε άλλο εκτός από το διορθωμένο κείμενο.

Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο προέρχεται από ένα κλασικό σχόλιο- είναι γραμμένο κυρίως σε μια σύγχρονη γλώσσα (αγγλικά, γαλλικά, γερμανικά ή ιταλικά) και μπορεί να περιέχει αλληλουχίες λέξεων σε αρχαίες γλώσσες (αρχαία ελληνικά και λατινικά). Το προς διόρθωση κείμενο εμφανίζεται μετά το τμήμα "ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ ΠΡΟΣ ΔΙΟΡΘΩΣΗ:". Παρακαλείστε να τοποθετήσετε τη διορθωμένη έκδοση του κειμένου μετά το τμήμα "ΔΙΟΡΘΩΜΕΝΟ ΚΕΙΜΕΝΟ:". Μην γράψετε τίποτε άλλο εκτός από το διορθωμένο κείμενο.

ocr.region: und Reden von 879—924 ein Sy- stem bilden, dessen Gliederung in Gesang und Rede sich ganz gleich wiederholt von 925— 970, so hat Schöll die drei letzten Verse, welche über die genaue Responsion hinaus- gehen, für unächt erklärt, Andere haben 969 und 972. 73 verdächtigt. Allein an sich hat das wiederholte Wenden und Drehen derselben Ge- danken bei so grossem Schmerze nichts Auffallendes und strenge Re- sponsion in den lamben ist nicht erforderlich. V. 969 steht der weib- lichen Sophistik wohl an; 972. 73 sind gerade hier von ergreifender Wirkung: ‚Ihm selbst ist wohl, die Fürsten werden ihn schon ver- missen, sie, die sich seinen Tod nieht zuschreiben dürfen; mir aber hat er ‚schweren Kummer hinter- lassen. Vgl. Trach. 41 πλὴν ἐμοὶ πικρὰς ’Adivas αὐτοῦ προσβαλὼν ἀποίχεται. 974. Teukros ruft hinter der Scene. 976. ἐπίσκοπον, ἐστοχασμέ- vor, συνῳδόν, wie Enioxonos To- ξότης = ö τυγχάνων τοῦ σκοποῦ. 978. ἀρ’ nunöinxd σε, habe

Ajax, whose mother was Eriboea (569). —τὸν εἰσαεὶ .. χρόνον : the phrase τὸν ἀεὶ χρόνον is frequent. The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Cp. Thuc. I. II § 1 (the Greeks at Troy) φαίνονται...πρὸς γεωργίαν τῆς Χερσονήσου τραπόμενοι καὶ λῃστείαν τῆς τροφῆς ἀπορίᾳ. The Iliad glances at such predatory expeditions (e.g. I. 366; 9. 328).—Note the light touch with which the poet accounts for the absence of Teucer—a necessity of the plot, since Teucer might have averted his brotherʼs suicide. 344 . ἀνοίγετε: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house generally; Aesch. Ch. 877 ἀλλʼ ἀνοίξατε: Ter. Adelph. 4. 4. 26 aperite, aliquis. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

ocr.region: und Reden von 879—924 ein Sy- stem bilden, dessen Gliederung in Gesang und Rede sich ganz gleich wiederholt von 925— 970, so hat Schöll die drei letzten Verse, welche über die genaue Responsion hinaus- gehen, für unächt erklärt, Andere haben 969 und 972. 73 verdächtigt. Allein an sich hat das wiederholte Wenden und Drehen derselben Ge- danken bei so grossem Schmerze nichts Auffallendes und strenge Re- sponsion in den lamben ist nicht erforderlich. V. 969 steht der weib- lichen Sophistik wohl an; 972. 73 sind gerade hier von ergreifender Wirkung: ‚Ihm selbst ist wohl, die Fürsten werden ihn schon ver- missen, sie, die sich seinen Tod nieht zuschreiben dürfen; mir aber hat er ‚schweren Kummer hinter- lassen. Vgl. Trach. 41 πλὴν ἐμοὶ πικρὰς ’Adivas αὐτοῦ προσβαλὼν ἀποίχεται. 974. Teukros ruft hinter der Scene. 976. ἐπίσκοπον, ἐστοχασμέ- vor, συνῳδόν, wie Enioxonos To- ξότης = ö τυγχάνων τοῦ σκοποῦ. 978. ἀρ’ nunöinxd σε, habe

Ajax, whose mother was Eriboea (569). —τὸν εἰσαεὶ .. χρόνον : the phrase τὸν ἀεὶ χρόνον is frequent. The separation of τὸν εἰσαεὶ from χρόνον deserves notice, as suggesting the possibility hat τὸν ἀεἰ may sometimes have been used (without χρό- νον) as = 'for ever ʼ: a usage which, how- ever, lacks proof: see on El. 1075.— λεηλατήσει: he had gone to the uplands of Mysia (720), 'in pursuit of foesʼ (564) to be despoiled. Cp. Thuc. I. II § 1 (the Greeks at Troy) φαίνονται...πρὸς γεωργίαν τῆς Χερσονήσου τραπόμενοι καὶ λῃστείαν τῆς τροφῆς ἀπορίᾳ. The Iliad glances at such predatory expeditions (e.g. I. 366; 9. 328).—Note the light touch with which the poet accounts for the absence of Teucer—a necessity of the plot, since Teucer might have averted his brotherʼs suicide. 344 . ἀνοίγετε: a usual form of summons, addressed to no particular per- son, but to the inmates of the house generally; Aesch. Ch. 877 ἀλλʼ ἀνοίξατε: Ter. Adelph. 4. 4. 26 aperite, aliquis. Ajax had πρόσπολοι, though they were not at this time in the house (539).—We should not explain the plur. as addressed by the choregus to the choreutae and Tecmessa.

ΚΕΊΜΕΝΟ ΠΡΟΣ ΔΙΌΡΘΩΣΗ:
1130. v ψέξαιμι, ich sollte .., fragt Men. verwundert, da er nicht begreift, wodurch er die göttlichen Satzungen (vgl. 1343. Ant. 450 ff. 1070 ff.) missachten sollte, worauf ihm Teukros sagt, inwie- fern er dieses thue, wogegen sich dann Men. verantwortet. Teukros erweitert den speciellen Gedanken durch θανόντας, um Menelaos’ Gottlosigkeit in desto grelleres Licht zu stellen. 1131. ei οὐκ Eds θάπτειν, näml. ψέγεις dam. vouovs. — Ueber παρών sagt Hermann: „Est in huiusmodi additamentis saepe indignalionis quaedam significa- tio, similiter ut cum nos dieimus: wenn du kommst, und die Todten nicht willst begraben lassen. ‘“ Vgl. 331. 1098.

ΚΕΊΜΕΝΟ ΠΡΟΣ ΔΙΟΡΘΩΣΗ:
1130. v pséxaimi, ich sollte.., fragt Men. verwundert, da er nicht begreift, wodurch er die göttlichen Satzungen (vgl. 1343. Ant. 450 ff. 1070 ff.) missachten sollte, worauf ihm Teukros sagt, inwie- fern er dieses thue, wogegen sich dann Men. verantwortet. Teukros erweitert den speciellen Gedanken durch thánontas, um Menelaos’ Gottlosigkeit in desto grelleres Licht zu stellen. 1131. ei ouk Eds tháptein, näml. pségeis dam. vouovs. — Ueber parṓn sagt Hermann: „Est in huiusmodi additamentis saepe indignalionis quaedam significa- tio, similiter ut cum nos dieimus: wenn du kommst, und die Todten nicht willst begraben lassen. ‘“ Vgl. 331. 1098.

1130. v pséxaimi, ich sollte.., fragt Men. verwundert, da er nicht begreift, wodurch er die göttlichen Satzungen (vgl. 1343. Teukros erweitert den speciellen Gedanken durch thánontas, um Menelaos’ Gottlosigkeit in desto grelleres Licht zu stellen. 1131. ei ouk Eds tháptein, näml. pségeis dam. vouovs. — Ueber parṓn sagt Hermann: „Est in huiusmodi additamentis saepe indignalionis quaedam significa- tio, similiter ut cum nos dieimus: wenn du kommst, und die Todten nicht willst begraben lassen. ‘“ Vgl. 331. 1098.

Ίσως ο Οδυσσέας θέλει να πει ότι ο ίδιος ο Αγαμέμνων θα γίνει τώρα πικρός, αν και μόλις τον αποκάλεσε τον καλύτερο του φίλο.

Das Epitheton ξιφοκτόνους vertritt die Stelle von aluarı (στάζων). 13. örov.. μάθῃς d. 1. ſage mir, was du erfahren willſt; ich kann dir Auskunft geben. 14. Bei Sophokles kommt nur die Form 496"a vor, bei Äſchylo8 auch die alte, feierliche Form Ἀθηναία. 15. ds iſt cauſal. Odyſſeus gibt an, warum er Athena ſofort erkannt habe. εὐμαθές iſt be- tont als Gegenſaß zu ἄποπτος (wenn ich dich auch nicht deutlich ſehe, er- kenne ich doch deutlich deine Stimme“). — ἐάν . 7/5, immer wie jetzt. — ἄποπτος („in der Ferne geſehen“) entſpricht der Illuſion, für welche Athena hoch in den Wolken ſchwebt. — 6uos ſchließt ſich dem Saße mit za: εἰ (ar) oder dem entſprechenden Participinm an. Kr. II 8 56, 13, 2. 16. Errao- πάζω poeri gibt kräftig die Metapher, die in ovrinu niht mehr gefühlt wird, und bezeichnet die unmittelbare, raſche Auffaſſung. 17. Die er- ſchütternde und das Herz erbeben machende Stimme der Göttin wird ver- glichen mit der διάτορος Τυρσηνικὴ σάλπιγξ, wie die Drommete, als deren Erfinder die Tyrrhener (Etrusker) galten, Äſch. Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraucht. - μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant. 675 f. 1081 f, ὅπου . . ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. - δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν τε vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (τίς) Kr. I § 61, 4, 5. - παρῇ: zu 496. 1083. Es findet ſich ἐξ οὐρίων (πνευμάτων) θεῖν, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobeck). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). - πεσεῖν: das Futurum wird durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter") vertreten. 1084. καὶ δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. - καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein⸗ ſtellend, heilſam. - Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 520 ἔσθ’ ὅπου τὸ δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ στένει. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. I § 46, 6, 9, Cu. § 153, 3, Kr. § 83, Ku. § 25, 3. - Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ σφε θάψω, κἂν ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν ἄρ’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.

Die Furcht galt den Griechen als Haltpunkt jeder geſellſchaftlichen Ordnung. 1077. γεννήσῃ hat Sopho⸗ kles nach Analogie von φύειν (πώγωνα, πτερά, ὀδόντας) gebraucht. - μέγα proleptiſches Prädikat wie δεινόν 1124. 1080. Vgl. Hom. E 351 αἰδομένων ἀνδρῶν πλέονες σόοι ἠὲ πέφανται, Ant. 675 f. 1081 f, ὅπου . . ταύτην τὴν πόλιν wie Phil. 456 ὅπου . . τούτους τοὺς ἄνδρας. - δρᾶν ἃ βούλεται (willkürlich ſchalten und walten): Subjekt iſt der bei ὑβρίζειν δρᾶν τε vorſchwebende allgemeine Begriff (τίς) Kr. I § 61, 4, 5. - παρῇ: zu 496. 1083. Es findet ſich ἐξ οὐρίων (πνευμάτων) θεῖν, πλεῖν, φέρεσθαι wie ἐξ οὐρίας πλεῖν, κομίζεσθαι (Beiſpiele bei Lobeck). In demſelben Sinne ſteht οὔρια θεῖν (mit günſtigem Winde fahren). - πεσεῖν: das Futurum wird durch χρόνῳ ποτὲ („früher oder ſpäter") vertreten. 1084. καὶ δέος, auch Furcht, nicht bloß Willkür. - καίριον, zu rechter Zeit ſich ein⸗ ſtellend, heilſam. - Vgl. Aſch. Eum. 520 ἔσθ’ ὅπου τὸ δεινὸν εὖ . . ξυμφέρει σωφρονεῖν ὑπὸ στένει. 1085 f. Über ἥδεσθαί τι Kr. I § 46, 6, 9, Cu. § 153, 3, Kr. § 83, Ku. § 25, 3. - Der Endreim hebt das Gleich⸗ mäßige des Inhalts. 1090. Vgl. Eur. Phön. 1657 Antigone: ἐγώ σφε θάψω, κἂν ἀπεννέπῃ πόλις. Kreon: σαυτὴν ἄρ’ ἐγγὺς τῷδε συνθάψεις νεκρῷ.
